                                                      37(2), 159–177



                                                      Muhammad Reza Pahlavi and the
                                                      Bahrain Question, 1968– 1970
                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI*



                                                      ABSTRACT This paper examines the role of Muhammad Reza Pahlavi, the late
                                                      Shah of Iran, in the secret Anglo-Iranian negotiations over Bahrain from January
                                                      1968 to March 1970. Despite a clear strategic imperative for abandoning Iran’s
                                                      claim to Bahrain in the wake of the British withdrawal from the Persian Gulf, the
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      Shah feared that such an act would be seen by the Iranian public as collusion with
                                                      the British to surrender Iranian territory, thereby further eroding the Pahlavi
                                                      monarchy’s precarious legitimacy. Drawing on British official papers and Iranian
                                                      oral histories and memoirs, this paper explores for the first time the story of these
                                                      secret negotiations and the extent to which the Shah’s diplomacy was constrained
                                                      by domestic considerations.



                                                      In March 1970, following 26 months of secret Anglo-Iranian negotiations, Shah
                                                      Muhammad Reza Pahlavi of Iran abandoned his country’s historic claim to
                                                      Bahrain.1 Diplomatic historians have given scant attention to the substance of
                                                      these negotiations, viewing them as a footnote in the story of Britain’s withdrawal
                                                      from the Persian Gulf between 1968 and 1971.2 Yet the Shah’s decision to
                                                      abandon Iran’s claim to Bahrain marked a turning point in Arab– Iranian relations
                                                      during the Cold War, setting the stage for Iran’s emergence as the leading power of
                                                      the Persian Gulf in the 1970s. The Bahrain negotiations provide a rare glimpse into
                                                      the conduct of Iranian diplomacy under Muhammad Reza Shah. The image of the
                                                      Shah that emerges from these negotiations is at odds with the views held by both
                                                      his supporters and detractors in the late 1960s. While the US Central Intelligence
                                                      Agency described him in 1968 as ‘a self-confident potentate, determined to assert
                                                      *Roham Alvandi, St. Catherine’s College, Manor Road, Oxford, OX1 3UJ, UK. E-mail:
                                                      roham.alvandi@politics.ox.ac.uk
                                                        1
                                                          See Husain Al-Baharna, ‘The Fact-finding Mission of the United Nations Secretary-General and the
                                                      Settlement of the Bahrain-Iran Dispute, May 1970’, The International and Comparative Law Quarterly, 22(3)
                                                      (1973), pp. 541–552; Erik Jensen, ‘The Secretary-General’s Use of Good Offices and the Question of Bahrain’,
                                                      Millennium: Journal of International Studies, 14(3) (1985), pp. 335 –348; Hooshang Moghtader, ‘The Settlement
                                                      of the Bahrain Question: A Study in Anglo-Iranian –United Nations Diplomacy’, Pakistan Horizon, 26(2) (1973),
                                                      pp. 16–29; and Rouhollah Ramazani, ‘The Settlement of the Bahrain Dispute’, Indian Journal of International
                                                      Law, 12(1) (1972), pp. 1 –14.
                                                        2
                                                          W. Taylor Fain, American Ascendance and British Retreat in the Persian Gulf Region (New York: Palgrave
                                                      Macmillan, 2008), pp. 185– 186; F. Gregory Gause, ‘British and American Policies in the Persian Gulf,
                                                      1968– 1973’, Review of International Studies, 11(4) (1985), p. 256; Wm. Roger Louis, ‘The British Withdrawal
                                                      from the Gulf, 1967–71’, The Journal of Imperial and Commonwealth History, 31(1) (2003), p. 98; and Simon
                                                      C. Smith, Britain’s Revival and Fall in the Gulf: Kuwait, Bahrain, Qatar, and the Trucial States, 1950–71
                                                      (London: RoutledgeCurzon, 2004), p. 99.

