                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                      his and Iran’s prerogatives against all comers’, the negotiations expose a deeply
                                                      insecure monarch, profoundly sensitive to the verdict of Iranian public opinion in
                                                      the conduct of his foreign policy.3 Indeed, the substance of these long and
                                                      torturous Anglo-Iranian negotiations focused on finding a face-saving formula for
                                                      the Shah to abandon Bahrain without appearing to have colluded with Britain to
                                                      surrender Iranian territory. Despite the Shah’s calculation that the abandonment of
                                                      Bahrain was necessary for ensuring regional security in the wake of Britain’s
                                                      withdrawal from the Persian Gulf, it took 26 months of secret negotiations with the
                                                      British for the Shah to agree to a mechanism that would allow him to abandon
                                                      Bahrain without further eroding his waning domestic legitimacy.
                                                         During the early Cold War, the security provided by Britain’s military presence
                                                      in the Persian Gulf afforded Iranian statesmen the freedom to focus on the
                                                      immediate threat posed by the Soviet Union to Iran’s northern border following
                                                      the 1946 Azerbaijan crisis.4 However, by the mid-1960s Muhammad Reza Shah
                                                      was keenly aware of Britain’s declining power in the region in the wake of the
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      Suez crisis. During his visit to Britain in March 1965, the Shah conveyed to Prime
                                                      Minister Harold Wilson his fear that a British withdrawal from the Gulf would
                                                      create a power vacuum that the radical Arab states and their Soviet patrons would
                                                      seek to fill.5 Following Britain’s ignoble withdrawal from Aden in November
                                                      1967, Goronwy Roberts, a junior Minister in the British Foreign Office, was
                                                      dispatched to reassure the Gulf’s rulers that Britain had no intention of
                                                      withdrawing from the region.6
                                                         The decline of Britain’s power in the Gulf coincided with two important trends
                                                      in Iranian foreign policy in the 1960s. First, the Shah sought to diminish Iran’s
                                                      dependence on the United States in favour of an ‘Independent National Policy’,
                                                      which he defined as ‘defending our country with our own capabilities and power’.7
                                                      The Shah could afford this newfound assertiveness thanks to a dramatic rise in
                                                      Iran’s oil revenues, which increased 25-fold between 1955 and 1968 from $33
                                                      million to $837.5 million. Iranian government spending increased seven-fold in
                                                      that same period, and by 1968 American aid accounted for less than six per cent of
                                                      Iranian government spending.8 Second, throughout the 1960s, Iran’s attention
                                                      increasingly turned from the Soviet threat from the north to the Arab threat from
                                                      the south. The Shah’s 1962 pledge to the Soviet Union that no foreign (i.e.
                                                      American) military bases would be allowed on Iranian soil led to a warming of
                                                      Soviet– Iranian relations, culminating in a number of technical and economic
                                                      agreements and a symbolic sale of around $100 million worth of unsophisticated
                                                      Soviet military hardware to Iran in 1966.9 As the direct Soviet threat diminished,
                                                        3
