                                                                                                                    THE BAHRAIN QUESTION, 1968–1970

                                                      the Shah became more concerned with the indirect threat posed by radical Arab
                                                      states, principally Egypt and Iraq, to stability in the Gulf. Iran and the radical
                                                      Arabs found themselves on opposite sides of the Cold War divide. While Iran had
                                                      allied with Britain in the 1955 Baghdad Pact and signed a defence agreement with
                                                      the United States in 1959, Egypt, Syria and later Iraq rejected the Baghdad Pact
                                                      and instead accepted Soviet patronage.
                                                         Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser portrayed the Shah as a Persian
                                                      imperialist who had allied himself with western imperialism and Zionism against
                                                      the Arab Nation. The Shah was alarmed by Egypt’s deployment in 1962 of
                                                      50,000 troops to support the Soviet-backed republicans in the civil war in North
                                                      Yemen.10 Another source of concern was that the People’s Democratic Republic
                                                      of Yemen (PDRY), which emerged in South Yemen following Britain’s
                                                      withdrawal from Aden in 1967, was funnelling Chinese and Soviet aid to the
                                                      rebellion against the Sultan of Oman in Dhofar.11 The Shah feared that these Arab
                                                      radicals would infiltrate the conservative monarchies of the Arabian Peninsula,
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      from where they could disrupt maritime exports of Iranian oil through the Strait
                                                      of Hormuz, attack Iran’s oil installation along the northern shore of the Gulf, and
                                                      pursue Arab territorial claims on Iran’s southern province of Khuzistan where
                                                      much of Iran’s oil reserves are located.12 As oil revenues accounted for more than
                                                      38 per cent of Iranian government spending in 1968, the stability and security of
                                                      the Gulf was vital for Iran.13 The Shah was keen to cultivate good relations with
                                                      the conservative Arab rulers of the Gulf, whom he invited regularly to Iran for
                                                      vacations and hunting trips. SAVAK,14 the Iranian intelligence service, had
                                                      established stations throughout the Lower Gulf and kept a close eye on all anti-
                                                      Iranian activities on the southern shore.15
                                                         These two trends in Iranian foreign policy framed the Shah’s reaction to the
                                                      Wilson Government’s announcement on 16 January 1968 that all British forces
                                                      ‘East of Suez’, including the Gulf, would be withdrawn by 1971. The British
                                                      Cabinet’s decision to cut defence spending was driven by the governing Labour
                                                      Party’s desire to achieve fiscal austerity in the face of severe economic pressure,
                                                      while avoiding painful cuts in social spending.16 Britain’s withdrawal posed a
                                                      major policy challenge for Iran, as the radical Arabs and their Soviet patrons
                                                      would undoubtedly hope to fill the power vacuum left by the British. The United
                                                      States, embroiled in the Vietnam conflict, was unable to take over the role
                                                      abandoned by Britain in the Gulf. As early as 1966, the Americans had expressed
                                                      their preference for a regional defence arrangement, and on 29 January 1968 US
                                                      Undersecretary of State Eugene Rostow publicly backed the idea of regional
                                                      security grouping involving Iran.17
                                                       10
                                                          Shahram Chubin and Sepehr Zabih, The Foreign Relations of Iran: a Developing State in a Zone of
                                                      Great-Power Conflict (Berkeley: University of California Press, 1974), pp. 140 –162.
                                                       11
                                                          Muhammad Ja‘far Chamankar, Buhran-i Zufar va rizhim-i Pahlavi (Tehran: Institute for Iranian
                                                      Contemporary Historical Studies, 2004), pp. 323 –331.
                                                       12
                                                          ‘Intelligence Memorandum: The Arab Threat to Iran’, 21 May 1966, Document No. 139, FRUS, XXII,
