                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                         Consistent with his ‘Independent National Policy,’ the Shah was anxious for Iran
                                                      to assume the leadership role in the Gulf abandoned by Britain and rejected by the
                                                      United States. When Goronwy Roberts returned to Tehran on 7 January 1968 to
                                                      inform the Shah of Britain’s dramatic policy reversal, the Shah proposed that Iran,
                                                      Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, and even Iraq should work together to provide aerial and
                                                      naval patrols of the waterway and consider signing a formal defence agreement.18
                                                      Indeed, Iran had been steadily augmenting its naval capabilities in the Gulf in
                                                      anticipation of such a role, including an order for four British destroyers in
                                                      February 1967.19 On the eve of the British withdrawal, Tehran, London and
                                                      Washington all supported a regional defence arrangement in the Gulf. The
                                                      principal obstacle to such Arab– Iranian cooperation was the outstanding border
                                                      disputes between Iran and her Arab neighbours, particularly on the Bahrain
                                                      question.20 There was therefore a clear strategic imperative for Iran to abandon its
                                                      claim to Bahrain in order to foster Arab– Iranian security cooperation in the Gulf in
                                                      the wake of the British withdrawal.
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                         Iran claimed to have exercised uninterrupted sovereignty over Bahrain since the
                                                      pre-Islamic era, except for the period of Portuguese occupation from 1522 to 1602.
                                                      Once Iran recaptured Bahrain from the Portuguese in 1602, it exercised
                                                      sovereignty over the archipelago until it was invaded by the al-Khalifah clan of the
                                                      Utubi tribe of Arabia in 1783. Based on a series of treaties and agreements signed
                                                      between the al-Khalifah and the British in the nineteenth century, Britain
                                                      recognized Bahrain as a ‘sovereign state in special treaty relations’ with Britain.
                                                      Throughout the nineteenth century, Iran protested to London over these treaties;
                                                      and in November 1927 took its dispute with Britain to the League of Nations,
                                                      without resolution. The issue re-emerged in 1951 when Iran demanded that the oil
                                                      nationalization laws passed by the Mosaddeq Government be applied not only to
                                                      the Anglo-Iranian Oil Company but also to the Bahrain Petroleum Company,
                                                      on the grounds that Bahrain was Iranian territory. Again, in November 1957, when
                                                      the Iranian Government redrew Iran’s provincial boundaries, it separated Bahrain
                                                      from the province of Fars and declared it Iran’s 14th province.21
                                                         However, in Muhammad Reza Shah’s estimation, Bahrain was of little
                                                      economic or strategic value to Iran. As the Shah explained to Amir Khosrow
                                                      Afshar, then Permanent Secretary of the Iranian Foreign Ministry, Bahrain’s oil
                                                      reserves were small and its once thriving pearl industry had declined. The
                                                      archipelago lay in the far south of the Gulf so it would be of little value in
                                                      securing the Strait of Hormuz, which was Iran’s paramount concern. Moreover,
                                                      any Iranian military intervention in Bahrain would probably result in violence and
                                                      civil strife.22 In his March 1965 meeting with Wilson, the Shah assured the
                                                      British that he had no intention of using force to resolve the Bahrain question.23
