                                                                                                                          THE BAHRAIN QUESTION, 1968–1970

                                                      This was in stark contrast to his views on the Gulf islands of Abu Musa and the
                                                      Greater and Lesser Tunbs,24 which were claimed by both Iran and the British
                                                      Protected States of Sharjah and Ras Al-Khaimah. The Shah considered these
                                                      Islands to be strategically vital given their proximity to the Strait of Hormuz, and
                                                      made it clear to Goronwy Roberts in their January 1968 meeting that if Iran could
                                                      not reach an agreement with the Protected States on their conflicting claims, he
                                                      was willing to unilaterally deploy troops on these Islands.25 Given his willingness
                                                      to abandon Iran’s claim to Bahrain and his determination to enforce Iranian
                                                      sovereignty over the Islands, the Shah clearly hoped that such a quid pro quo
                                                      could be achieved as part of a ‘package deal’ with the British. While such a deal
                                                      was never struck in the course of the Bahrain negotiations, the issue did emerge
                                                      periodically throughout the talks with the British.26
                                                         By the 1960s the notion of Bahrain as Iranian territory had, in the words of one
                                                      Iranian journalist and publisher of the day, ‘entered the subconscious of the Iranian
                                                      people’.27 A consensus existed, particularly among Iranian intellectuals, that
                                                      Iran’s historical and legal claim to Bahrain was irrefutable.28 The Bahrain question
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      was particularly emotive as it involved a dispute with Britain, an imperial power
                                                      that had deeply penetrated Iran’s political and economic life for much of the
                                                      nineteenth and twentieth centuries. A succession of British envoys in Iran attest to
                                                      the popular Iranian perception of perfidious Albion as the sinister hidden hand in
                                                      Iranian politics.29 Britain’s role in overthrowing the nationalist Mosaddeq
                                                      Government in 1953 and restoring the Shah to power not only entrenched this
                                                      widespread Anglophobia, but also eroded Muhammad Reza Shah’s nationalist
                                                      credentials.30 The Shah made efforts to bolster his image as an authentic Iranian
                                                      nationalist by contrasting his ‘positive nationalism’, which he defined as ‘a policy
                                                      of maximum political and economic independence’, with Mosaddeq’s
                                                      ‘negativism’, which had ‘led straight to the sort of political and economic chaos
                                                      which foreign agents found ideal for their purposes’.31 Therefore, despite the
                                                      strategic imperatives for giving up the claim to Bahrain, any appearance of
                                                      collusion with the British to surrender Bahrain would have further jeopardized the
                                                      Shah’s domestic legitimacy. Writing only a few years after the Bahrain
