                                                                                                                                                               163
                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                      negotiations were concluded, Shahram Chubin suggested that there were certain
                                                      domestic constraints on the Shah’s ability to relinquish the claim to Bahrain.32
                                                      With the passage of nearly 40 years and the availability of British official papers
                                                      and Iranian oral histories we can now examine how these domestic factors
                                                      constrained the Shah’s decision-making on the Bahrain question.
                                                         The intermittent Anglo-Iranian negotiations on Bahrain can be separated into
                                                      five stages. From January to August 1968, the discussions focused on the Shah’s
                                                      demand for a plebiscite in Bahrain. From August to December 1968, as Iran’s
                                                      relations with the Arab states gradually improved, the negotiations culminated in
                                                      the Shah’s decision to forgo a plebiscite. The major turning point came with the
                                                      Shah’s 6 January 1969 New Delhi statement, when he publicly committed himself
                                                      to relinquishing Iran’s claim to Bahrain. From January to August 1969, the British
                                                      and Iranians focused on the idea of a UN Mission going to Bahrain to ascertain the
                                                      wishes of the Bahraini people, thereby providing the Shah with a face-saving
                                                      mechanism to abandon Iran’s claim. Although the negotiations ground to a halt in
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      the summer over the UN Mission’s method of procedure, the impasse was broken
                                                      and from September to December 1969 discussions on the details of the UN
                                                      Mission continued, culminating in the joint informal approach to UN Secretary-
                                                      General U. Thant on 28 December. From December 1969 to March 1970, the talks
                                                      centred on the wording of the formal Iranian approach to U. Thant, which finally
                                                      took place on 9 March 1970, thus ending the negotiations.
                                                         The negotiations began with Goronwy Roberts’ audience with the Shah on 7
                                                      January 1968, where he conveyed Britain’s decision to leave the Gulf by 1971.
                                                      The Shah expressed to Roberts his desire to find a face-saving way for him
                                                      to abandon Iran’s claim to Bahrain. ‘Thinking aloud’, he posited that ‘some
                                                      presentational device’ was needed and suggested that a ‘plebiscite’ be held in
                                                      Bahrain to ascertain whether the Bahrainis wished to be part of Iran or not.33 If, as
                                                      expected, the Bahrainis voted for independence from Iran, the Shah could then
                                                      portray his relinquishment of Iran’s claim to Bahrain as his magnanimous
                                                      acquiescence to the desire of the Bahraini people for self-determination, rather
                                                      than collusion with Britain to surrender Iranian territory. Sir Denis Wright, the
                                                      British Ambassador in Tehran, recorded in his 1968 annual review that the Shah’s
                                                      paramount fear was that he would ‘go down in history as the man who lightly
                                                      abandoned his country’s “14th Province”’.34 Both the British and the al-Khalifah
                                                      were opposed to a plebiscite, fearing that it would ignite sectarian tensions
                                                      in Bahrain where the ruling al-Khalifah dynasty were Sunni Muslims but
                                                      the majority of the population were Shi‘i Muslims as in neighbouring Iran.
                                                      A plebiscite on whether or not to be part of Iran could easily become a referendum
                                                      on the Shi‘i or Sunni character of Bahrain. As Roberts explained to the Shah, a
                                                      plebiscite would ‘unleash forces’ of sectarianism and ‘increase the danger’ of
                                                      instability in Bahrain and the Gulf.35
                                                         The persistence of the Iranian claim to Bahrain hampered Iranian efforts to
                                                      pursue regional cooperation in the wake of the British decision to withdraw. The
                                                      Shah had received the Ruler of Kuwait in Tehran in January 1968 and was set to
                                                       32
                                                          Shahram Chubin, Iran and International Organization: The Use of the UN on Selected Issues 1960–1971
