                                                      make a state visit to Saudi Arabia to discuss the future of the Gulf with King
                                                      Faisal. However, on 17 January, at the conclusion of a three-day visit to Saudi
                                                      Arabia by Sheikh Issa, the Ruler of Bahrain, the Saudis declared that they would
                                                      ‘fully endorse and effectively support the Bahrayn [sic ] government in all
                                                      circumstances’. They also proposed building a causeway linking Bahrain to Saudi
                                                      Arabia. The Shah interpreted these Saudi moves as a repudiation of Iran’s claim to
                                                      Bahrain and promptly cancelled his impending trip to Saudi Arabia.36 Iran’s
                                                      relations with the Arabs continued to deteriorate due to the Bahrain issue, and
                                                      Tehran increasingly took a unilateral, rather than multilateral, approach to regional
                                                      security. On 27 January, Iranian Prime Minister Amir Abbas Hoveyda declared
                                                      that Iran was the ‘most powerful’ state in the Gulf and that ‘there is no doubt’ that
                                                      Iran would defend her ‘rights’ in the region. He emphasized that Britain could not
                                                      ‘leave through the front door only to re-enter through the back door’, a reference to
                                                      British collusion with the Arab rulers of the Gulf. Hoveyda stressed that Gulf
                                                      security was the exclusive responsibility of the littoral states and that external
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      powers should be excluded.37
                                                         The prospects for any Anglo-Iranian deal on Bahrain suffered a major blow
                                                      when Britain supported the 26 February 1968 announcement by Bahrain, the
                                                      Trucial States, and Qatar that they would unite to form a single Arab federation.
                                                      The Iranians interpreted Britain’s support for the inclusion of Bahrain as an
                                                      attempt to make Bahrain’s independence from Iran a fait accompli. They were
                                                      convinced that the British were behind the federation idea and denounced this
                                                      attempt by Britain to unilaterally hand over Iranian territory to the Arabs. The
                                                      Shah made his displeasure clear in a speech in Isfahan on 13 March. Clearly
                                                      frustrated that Iran’s calls for regional cooperation had been rebuffed, and angry at
                                                      the Anglo-Arab collusion on Bahrain, the Shah declared that Iran would:
                                                         reciprocate in kind to foreign attitudes towards us, not that the other should expect
                                                         unreserved friendship from us in exchange perhaps for a glance of affection. I must also
                                                         declare here that if ever our present friends do not respect our interests, especially in the
                                                         Persian Gulf, they should expect a similar attitude on our part.38
                                                         Aware of the Shah’s anger and suspicion, Ambassador Wright sought to ‘play
                                                      for time’ in the hope that ‘second thoughts will prevail here as they have done
                                                      so often in the past’.39 British Foreign Secretary Michael Stewart instructed
                                                      Wright to tell the Shah that Britain was examining the possibility of a ‘package
                                                      deal’ involving a renunciation of Iran’s claim to Bahrain in exchange for the return
                                                      of the Islands to Iran. However, he instructed Wright to avoid raising the Shah’s
                                                      expectations too high. Instead, he should point out ‘that Bahrain, Abu Musa and
                                                      the Tunbs affect three different Arab states and cannot be packaged arbitrarily by
                                                      H.M.G.’.40 The British proposal was met with lukewarm enthusiasm by the Shah.
                                                      A package deal would do little to assuage his fears about the verdict of Iranian
                                                      public opinion. When Wright questioned the extent to which Iranian public
                                                      opinion was even aware of the issue, the Shah disagreed, arguing that the Foreign
                                                       36
