                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                      Ministry and the armed forces were certainly aware.41 In London, some in the
                                                      Foreign Office wondered whether the Shah’s concerns about public opinion were a
                                                      ‘disingenuous’ negotiating tactic.42 After all, what would he have to fear from
                                                      Iran’s state-controlled media and muzzled domestic opposition? From his vantage
                                                      point in Tehran, Wright forcefully argued that the Shah was ‘perfectly sincere’
                                                      when expressing his fears, and had often told him that:
                                                           in this singularly ungrateful country he cannot for one moment afford to give the
                                                           impression that he is slipping, going soft, giving things away, etc. or everyone would be at
                                                           his throat. These dangers may exist merely in his own mind only, but they are very real to
                                                           him.43
                                                      In effect, it did not matter whether domestic opposition to abandoning Bahrain was
                                                      real or apparent. What mattered was that the Shah, Iran’s sole foreign policy
                                                      decision-maker, was convinced that public opinion would be against the decision.
                                                         There was little hope that a ‘package deal’ could provide a solution to the
                                                      Bahrain question. The British were not sincere in offering a deal, as they had no
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      intention of compelling the Protected States to acquiesce to Iran’s seizure of Abu
                                                      Musa and the Tunbs. Stewart had written in March 1968 of the difficulties for
                                                      Britain ‘in appearing to encourage the surrender of Arab territory’.44 Furthermore,
                                                      a package deal did little to allay the Shah’s fears about the verdict of Iranian public
                                                      opinion. Consequently, by early August 1968 the negotiations were paralysed.
                                                      On 6 August the Shah received Wright in Ramsar on the Caspian shore where the
                                                      Monarch was vacationing. Wright recounted that, in their discussions, the Shah
                                                      insisted on a plebiscite in Bahrain on the grounds that:
                                                           it would not be enough to tell his people that Bahrain’s oil was running out and her pearls
                                                           had already done so. He must be able to say that the majority of Bahrainis had expressed a
                                                           wish for independence from Iran.
                                                      The Shah warned that if the proposed Arab federation declared independence with
                                                      Bahrain as a member, Iran would oppose them, and that if Bahrain independently
                                                      became a member of the UN, Iran would leave the world body.45
                                                         Despite the setbacks of the spring, Iran launched a diplomatic offensive in the
                                                      summer to improve relations with her Arab neighbours. In August 1968 the
                                                      Iranians agreed, through Kuwaiti mediation, to secret face-to-face talks in Geneva
                                                      between the Iranian Foreign Minister and the Deputy Ruler of Bahrain.46 Foreign
                                                      Minister Ardeshir Zahedi, one of the most hawkish voices in Tehran on the
                                                      Bahrain issue, delayed the meeting for some months. He had famously flown into a
                                                      rage at a reception at the British Embassy in Tehran on 11 November 1967, when
                                                      Goronwy Roberts had expressed support for Bahrain’s membership in some of the
                                                      specialized agencies of the United Nations. Zahedi warned Roberts that, ‘if this is
                                                      the way you are going to behave, I shall resign, take a gun, sail there [Bahrain], and
                                                      fight for the beloved’. Recalling Zahedi’s reference to ‘the beloved’, Wright
                                                      41
