                                                      mischievously recorded that ‘Those of us present who knew about Mr. Zahedi’s
                                                      hobbies had to restrain ourselves from asking “is she blonde or brunette?”’.47
                                                      Zahedi’s relations with Wright were strained throughout his tenure as Foreign
                                                      Minister.48 Wright’s contempt for the Foreign Minister was palpable in his
                                                      dispatches to London, where he described Zahedi as ‘unbalanced’, ‘thoroughly
                                                      devious and hostile’.49 By the autumn of 1968, when Iran’s diplomatic offensive
                                                      with the Arabs seemed to be bearing fruit, the Shah may well have concluded that
                                                      Zahedi’s difficult relationship with the British Ambassador was an obstacle to
                                                      reaching a settlement with London. This may explain why the Shah appointed
                                                      Zahedi’s deputy, Amir Khosrow Afshar, as the chief Iranian negotiator on
                                                      the Bahrain question. Afshar was the ideal choice as he had previously served as
                                                      Iran’s Ambassador in London and was considered something of an ‘Anglophile’,
                                                      yet he also enjoyed very warm relations with Zahedi who referred to him as his
                                                      ‘cousin’.50
                                                         In the first of the secret bi-lateral meetings with the Bahrainis in September
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      1968, Afshar suggested three possible mechanisms for the resolution of the
                                                      Bahrain question. The first was a plebiscite, which the Shah had suggested in
                                                      January. The second was to refer the dispute for arbitration to the International
                                                      Court of Justice (ICJ) at The Hague. The third was to refer the matter to the United
                                                      Nations for mediation. According to both British and Iranian sources, the Iranians
                                                      continued to favour a plebiscite while the Bahrainis vehemently rejected it.
                                                      Although the two parties could not come to any preliminary agreement, they
                                                      decided that these secret bi-lateral contacts should continue.51 The Bahrainis kept
                                                      the British informed of the secret dialogue and, in the subsequent discussions in
                                                      the British Foreign Office, Foreign Secretary Michael Stewart raised the idea
                                                      of mediation by a representative of the UN Secretary-General.52 The British
                                                      were concerned that a plebiscite would be ‘fraught with difficulty and danger’,
                                                      while referral to the ICJ ‘would likely take so long’.53 Lord Caradon, British
                                                      Ambassador to the United Nations in New York, expressed grave doubts about the
                                                      idea of involving a Personal Representative of the UN Secretary-General (PRSG),
                                                      but conceded that it ‘would be the form of action least likely to be dangerous’.54
                                                         Nonetheless, for any progress to be made on the UN option, Iran would have to
                                                      drop her demand for a plebiscite. While the Iranians had the same reservations as
                                                      the British about the ICJ and the United Nations, they saw a plebiscite as the only
                                                      face-saving way to abandon the claim to Bahrain. As the Shah explained to Wright
                                                      on 28 October 1968, ‘For the people of Iran to accept the abandonment of their
