                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                      claim to Bahrain it was essential that they should realise that it had been dropped
                                                      in conformity with internationally recognised procedures’.55 For the Shah a
                                                      plebiscite was the only way to ensure that the decision bore the stamp of ‘legality
                                                      and recognised procedure’, rather than appearing as ‘the decision of one man’. If
                                                      the British and the Bahrainis would not acquiesce to a plebiscite, the Shah warned,
                                                      Iran would have no choice but to bring a complaint against Britain at the UN
                                                      Security Council.56
                                                         The impasse over the plebiscite issue was finally broken following a
                                                      rapprochement between Iran and Saudi Arabia. En route to a state visit to the
                                                      United States, the Shah stopped in Jeddah on 3 June 1968 to meet with King
                                                      Faisal. By August, Saudi– Iranian negotiations were underway on the resolution of
                                                      the long-standing dispute over their maritime border in Gulf, culminating in the
                                                      signing of a continental shelf agreement in October. This cleared the way for the
                                                      Shah’s visit to Saudi Arabia from 9 to 14 November, where the main topic of
                                                      conversation was the future of Bahrain and the Gulf. King Faisal advised the Shah
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      that all of the Arab rulers of the Gulf were opposed to a plebiscite in Bahrain, and
                                                      he secured a commitment from the Shah to consider other alternatives.57
                                                         A few weeks later, during discussions between Wright and Senator Abbas
                                                      Masoudi in Tehran, the idea of sending a UN Mission to ascertain the Bahraini
                                                      people’s wishes re-emerged. Masoudi was Vice President of the Iranian Senate
                                                      and publisher of Ettela’at, a national daily newspaper in Iran. He was well
                                                      received by the Arab rulers of the Gulf because of his business interests in their
                                                      sheikhdoms and often served as a back-channel for communications between them
                                                      and the Shah. Wright asked Masoudi to see whether a UN Mission would be
                                                      acceptable to the Shah as an alternative to a plebiscite. Two days later Masoudi
                                                      confirmed that the Shah had approved the idea, ‘provided the findings of any UN
                                                      Mission could be given an internationally recognised legal basis’.58 In his report to
                                                      London, Wright presented the proposal as an Iranian initiative, in the hope of
                                                      winning the support of his Arabist colleagues in the Foreign Office who were more
                                                      sympathetic to the Bahraini position.59 The proposal was in line with the internal
                                                      discussions the British had conducted in October, and the Foreign Secretary
                                                      authorized Wright to pursue the idea, instructing him to secure:
                                                           an understanding with the Shah ab initio that the purpose would be to affirm the ‘Arabism’
                                                           of Bahrain but in such a way as to get the Iranian government off the hook. It would thus
                                                           amount to a prearranged public relations exercise.60
                                                         On Christmas Eve 1968, the Shah confirmed to Wright that he would not insist
                                                      on a plebiscite, or even the mention of the word ‘plebiscite’ in the proposed UN
                                                      Mission’s terms of reference. His sole concern was that the UN Mission should
                                                      determine the ‘will of the people of Bahrain’ in a way that would be ‘legally and
                                                      internationally recognisable’. In a sign of his sincere desire to find a prompt
                                                      solution to the Bahrain question, the Shah informed Wright that he should deal
