                                                      only with Afshar, and not the troublesome Zahedi, on this issue.61 Just days earlier,
                                                      the second secret meeting between Afshar and the Bahrainis had taken place in
                                                      Geneva.62 The Bahrainis informed the British that the atmosphere of the talks had
                                                      improved and that the Iranians were determined to resolve the matter as quickly as
                                                      possible. Afshar had agreed that a plebiscite would only lead to confrontation, and
                                                      so the two parties agreed to study the UN option.63 The task ahead was to work out
                                                      the details of the UN exercise. When he returned to Tehran from Geneva, Afshar
                                                      met with Wright and emphasized that the Shah wanted to avoid any appearance of
                                                      collusion between Britain and Iran ‘for domestic reasons’.64
                                                         Prior to January 1969, knowledge of these Anglo-Iranian discussions on
                                                      Bahrain was a tightly kept secret. In Tehran, some Foreign Ministry officials were
                                                      aware that negotiations were being conducted, but only a handful of people had
                                                      any knowledge of the substance of the talks.65 However, the Shah’s intentions
                                                      were made public on 6 January 1969, when during a state visit to India he was
                                                      asked at a press conference in New Delhi about Iran’s claim to Bahrain. He
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      responded that Iran could not accept that ‘this island which was separated from our
                                                      country should be just offered by the British to other people at our expense’.
                                                      However, he publicly declared for the first time that, ‘if the people of Bahrain do
                                                      not want to join my country first of all, it is against our principle to use force in
                                                      order to reattach this land of ours’. Iran would not use force because ‘it is not even
                                                      intelligent to try to occupy a land against the will of its people’.66
                                                         The Shah’s New Delhi statement was the major turning point in the negotiations
                                                      with Britain and came as a shock to his advisers, including Zahedi.67 For the first
                                                      time, an Iranian monarch had given public notice that Iran was willing to
                                                      relinquish her claim to Bahrain. After 12 months of Anglo-Iranian discussions and
                                                      two secret meetings with the Bahrainis in Geneva, the Shah had agreed to forgo a
                                                      plebiscite in favour of a UN Mission that would ascertain the wishes of the
                                                      Bahraini people. With his unprecedented New Delhi statement, the Shah sought to
                                                      present his decision as a bold and magnanimous Iranian initiative. In Wright’s
                                                      assessment, the statement was sincere, as the Shah avoided any mention of a
                                                      plebiscite, in line with his private understanding with the British.68
                                                         Having agreed to a UN Mission as a face-saving way for Iran to relinquish
                                                      her claim, an array of difficult questions remained. Who would approach the
                                                      UN and how would the approach be made? What would the Mission’s terms of
                                                      reference be? How would the Mission ascertain the wishes of the Bahraini
                                                      people? At the outset, there was little consensus between Britain, Iran and UN
                                                      Secretary-General U Thant on any of these questions, all of which would have
                                                      to be resolved before the UN Mission could proceed. The British proposed that
                                                      Iran and Britain jointly approach U Thant to ask him to lend his Good Offices
                                                      to resolving the dispute. This was unacceptable to Iran, as a joint approach
