                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                      would appear, in Afshar’s words, as ‘collusion’ between Britain and Iran to fix
                                                      the UN Mission’s findings in advance. This would destroy the credibility of the
                                                      Mission’s findings in the eyes of the Iranian public. Instead, the Iranians
                                                      proposed that they bring their dispute with Britain to the UN Security Council,
                                                      which would then request U Thant to provide his Good Offices. Recourse to the
                                                      Security Council was unacceptable to the British, who feared that it would
                                                      frame the issue as a confrontation between Iran and Britain and invite
                                                      intervention by hostile members of the Council, particularly the Soviet Union.69
                                                      The Bahrainis were equally displeased with the idea of approaching the
                                                      Security Council, and instead floated the idea of referring the matter for
                                                      arbitration to a committee of four friendly regional states.70
                                                         Little progress was made at the third secret meeting between the Bahrainis
                                                      and the Iranians on 2 – 3 March 1969. The Iranians had agreed to drop their
                                                      demands for a plebiscite, but they continued to insist on an approach to the
                                                      Security Council. The Bahrainis raised the earlier British proposal for a joint
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      Anglo-Iranian approach to U Thant, which Afshar agreed to discuss with the
                                                      Shah.71 Once again, the Iranians proposed a compromise solution to break the
                                                      impasse. On 15 March, the Shah informed Wright that he would not press for
                                                      an initial approach to the Security Council. Nor would he accept a joint
                                                      approach to U Thant, which would create the impression that Britain and Iran
                                                      had colluded to fix the UN Mission’s findings. Instead, the Shah proposed that
                                                      Iran alone would make the initial approach to the UN Secretary-General. Once
                                                      the UN Mission had ascertained the wishes of the Bahraini people, Iran would
                                                      accept those findings if they were endorsed by the Security Council.72 This
                                                      formula would avoid the appearance of collusion while also giving the Shah’s
                                                      decision to abandon Bahrain the Security Council’s seal of approval. This
                                                      Iranian proposal would constitute the basic framework for the settlement of the
                                                      Bahrain question.
                                                         Sensing that they were close to an understanding with the British on Bahrain,
                                                      the Iranians sought to tie the resolution of the Bahrain question to their claims on
                                                      the Islands. On 19 March 1969, Asadollah Alam, the Shah’s Court Minister and
                                                      most trusted adviser, informed Wright that no agreement could be reached on
                                                      Bahrain until the issue of the Islands had been settled. The Iranians feared that if
                                                      the Bahrain issue were settled first, thus ending Iran’s opposition to an Arab
                                                      federation in the Gulf, then the Protected States would have little incentive to
                                                      negotiate with Iran over the other Islands.73 Alam records Wright’s suggestion that
                                                      ‘a solution to the problem of Bahrain will almost certainly encourage the
                                                      establishment of the Federation of Arab Emirates, at which stage Iran might well
                                                      occupy Abu Musa in the interests of joint security in the Gulf’. Wright assured
                                                      Alam that Iran could ‘depend on support from the British, should this happen’.74
                                                      However, the following evening when Alam telephoned Wright to tell him that he
