                                                      had informed the Shah of their conversation, he asked Wright for his assurance
                                                      that if Iran abandoned her claim to Bahrain, Britain would acquiesce to Iran’s
                                                      seizure of the Islands. Wright responded that he saw ‘no such possibility’.75
                                                      As Alam records, the Shah was clearly ‘disappointed’ by the British response, as
                                                      he was sure that he had ‘bagged’ the Islands after his New Delhi statement.76
                                                         While some have speculated that such a ‘package deal’ was reached between
                                                      Britain and Iran, there is little evidence to support this claim.77 Afshar, the
                                                      principal Iranian negotiator in the Bahrain talks, categorically denied that any such
                                                      deal was struck.78 In April 1968 and again in March 1969 the British did raise
                                                      Iranian expectations that a concession on Bahrain would engender British
                                                      goodwill towards Iran when it came to settling the Islands dispute. However, when
                                                      the Iranians sought explicit confirmation of such a quid pro quo, they were met
                                                      with a negative British response. The matter was put to rest on 27 May 1969 when
                                                      Michael Stewart was received by the Shah in Tehran. The Shah again asked the
                                                      Foreign Secretary for his assurance that once the Bahrain issue was solved Britain
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      would acquiesce to Iran’s seizure of the Islands. Stewart’s response was that ‘no
                                                      British government would be able to give such an assurance’. Nonetheless, the
                                                      Shah seemed satisfied with Stuart’s pledge that Britain would use her considerable
                                                      influence over the Protected States to urge them to reach an understanding with
                                                      Iran on the Islands.79
                                                         From April to September 1969 the discussions focused on how the Bahrain
                                                      question would be brought to the attention of the United Nations, the terms of
                                                      reference of the proposed UN Mission, the method by which the Mission would
                                                      ascertain the wishes of the Bahraini people, and finally how its findings would be
                                                      transmitted to and accepted by Iran. The Mission was clearly a pre-arranged public
                                                      relations exercise, designed as a face-saving way for the Shah to relinquish Iran’s
                                                      claim to Bahrain. Although every detail of the Mission would be prearranged, the
                                                      Shah hoped to avoid any appearance of Anglo-Iranian collusion in order to
                                                      preserve the credibility of the Mission’s findings in the eyes of the Iranian public.
                                                      This would be difficult to achieve, as both the British and the Bahrainis insisted
                                                      that every step of the process be scripted and tightly controlled to ensure that the
                                                      exercise did not ignite sectarian tensions in Bahrain.
                                                         The negotiations stalled in the summer of 1969 when the British and the
                                                      Iranians could not agree on the method by which the UN Mission would ascertain
                                                      the wishes of the Bahraini people. The British, reflecting Bahraini anxieties,
                                                      wanted prior agreement on the Mission’s methodology. They envisaged that the
                                                      PRSG would go to Bahrain to speak with a designated list of community leaders
                                                      and civil society groups and then report back to the Security Council. The Iranians
                                                      wanted to leave the decision on methodology to the PRSG himself. As Afshar
                                                      explained to Wright on 19 July, Iran could not a priori give up the idea of a
