                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                      plebiscite in Bahrain. However, Iran was willing to acquiesce to canvassing
                                                      instead of a plebiscite if this was the choice of the PRSG. In this way,
                                                      responsibility for abandoning the idea of a plebiscite would be shifted from the
                                                      Shah to the United Nations, thereby avoiding any hint of collusion between Britain
                                                      and Iran to fix the Mission’s findings.80 This question of methodology threatened
                                                      to halt the negotiations entirely. The Shah was not insisting on a plebiscite, but for
                                                      the sake of appearances he wanted the PRSG to take responsibility for ruling it out.
                                                      The Shah wanted the UN Mission to appear to have acted independently and
                                                      legally so that the Iranian public would accept its findings, after which he could
                                                      graciously acquiesce to the genuine wishes of the Bahraini people. As Alam
                                                      explained to Wright in August, any appearance of collusion would leave the Shah
                                                      and his dynasty open to accusations that they had betrayed Iran. For the Shah to
                                                      agree in advance to the method of procedure was tantamount, in Alam’s words, to
                                                      ‘suicide, perhaps even treason’.81
                                                         The Shah was eager to quickly resolve the Bahrain question and he once again
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      compromised in order to break the deadlock on the methodology question. On 2
                                                      September 1969 he proposed to Wright that ‘provided he was kept in ignorance’,
                                                      the British and the Bahrainis could select any procedure they liked for the UN
                                                      Mission and could prepare the list of individuals and organizations that the PRSG
                                                      would consult in Bahrain. The British and the Bahrainis were free to make an
                                                      agreement with the United Nations about this procedure, but Iran should have no
                                                      official knowledge of it.82 As long as the British, Bahrainis and the United Nations
                                                      kept Iran in the dark, the Shah could deny any knowledge of collusion to script the
                                                      UN Mission’s findings. The British had kept UN Under-Secretary-General Ralph
                                                      Bunche informed of their discussions with the Iranians since December 1968.83
                                                      Bunche had made it clear to the British that U Thant would prefer both the British
                                                      and the Iranians to sign off on the methodology of the proposed UN Mission.84 In a
                                                      meeting in New York on 19 October 1969, the Shah informed U Thant that he was
                                                      happy for the United Nations to work out the details of the methodology with the
                                                      British.85 Nonetheless, U Thant was unwilling to go along with the Iranian desire
                                                      for official ignorance. His fear was that when the UN Mission found that the
                                                      Bahrainis sought independence, the Shah might cave-in to domestic pressure and
                                                      reject the Mission’s findings on the grounds that Iran had not been consulted. He
                                                      insisted that before Iran formally approached him, Britain and Iran should make a
                                                      joint informal approach to him and sign a memorandum for his own files
                                                      acknowledging agreement on the proposed Mission’s terms of reference and
                                                      methodology.86
                                                         The Secretary-General’s demands were unpalatable to the Iranians. By signing
                                                      off on the method of procedure, Iran would be complicit in fixing the UN
                                                      Mission’s findings in advance. Afshar warned the British on 23 December 1969
                                                      that:
