                                                           If U Thant communicated the method of operation to the Iranian Government in any form,
                                                           written or oral, formal or informal and even if someone just whispered in Vakil’s [Iranian
                                                           Ambassador to the UN] ear, the Iranians would say that they were opposed to this method
                                                           of operation.87
                                                      With this caveat, the joint informal approach to U Thant took place at his official
                                                      residence in New York on 28 December 1969. Iran’s Ambassador, Mehdi Vakil,
                                                      asked the Secretary-General whether he would be willing to exercise his Good
                                                      Offices to ascertain the wishes of the Bahraini people, on the basis of the terms of
                                                      reference agreed to by Britain and Iran. Vakil stated that Iran would leave it to U
                                                      Thant to determine ‘the most appropriate method’ for ascertaining the Bahraini
                                                      people’s wishes and he emphasized that his government did not wish to receive
                                                      any communication from the Secretary-General on the method of procedure. U
                                                      Thant agreed to provide his Good Offices, on the condition that there was
                                                      agreement between Britain and Iran on the terms of reference and methodology for
                                                      the proposed UN Mission. He did not ask the Iranians to sign a memorandum on
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      the methodology, but insisted on sending a vaguely worded summary of it to the
                                                      Iranians prior to their formal approach. The Iranian diplomats, realizing this was
                                                      a sine qua non for the Secretary-General, acquiesced.88 Indeed, the next day
                                                      a memorandum on the methodology of the UN Mission was delivered to Iran’s
                                                      Mission to the United Nations in New York without any response from the
                                                      Iranians.89
                                                         At the final hurdle, with the joint informal approach having been made, the
                                                      negotiations focused on the wording of the letter the Iranians would send to U
                                                      Thant, formally requesting the UN Secretary-General to lend his Good Offices.
                                                      Again, it was of paramount importance to the Iranians that the letter be devoid of
                                                      any hint of collusion with the British. A draft had been presented to the British on
                                                      29 January 1970, in which Iran requested U Thant to ascertain the ‘true wishes’ of
                                                      the ‘inhabitants’ of Bahrain with respect to their ‘future status’.90 The use of ‘true
                                                      wishes’ implied that it was not certain whether the Bahrainis wished to be
                                                      independent of Iran, as assumed by Britain and the al-Khalifah. The choice of
                                                      ‘inhabitants,’ rather than ‘people’, implied that the population of Bahrain did not
                                                      necessarily constitute an Arab nation separate from Iran. Furthermore, by
                                                      employing ‘future status’ the Iranians sought to distinguish the current status of
                                                      Bahrain as a province of Iran from Bahrain’s potential future status as an
                                                      independent state.
                                                         Wright travelled to St Moritz to settle the wording of the formal Iranian
                                                      approach with the Shah, who was then on his annual skiing vacation in
                                                      Switzerland. He met with Afshar and the Shah on 5 February 1970, and after some
                                                      hard bargaining begrudgingly agreed to the ‘future status’ and ‘true wishes’
                                                      wording, but refused to accept ‘inhabitants’. The Shah agreed in principle, and left
                                                      it to Afshar and Wright to finalize the text. After two hours of back and forth
                                                      between Wright and Afshar, the final text was agreed and approved by the Shah.91
                                                      However, Iran’s formal approach to U Thant was delayed until March, so that the
                                                      Bahrainis could make preparations for receiving the UN Mission. On 9 March
                                                      87
                                                           Wright (Tehran) to Foreign Office, 24 December 1969, FCO 8/954.
                                                      88
                                                           Caradon (New York) to Foreign Office, 28 December 1969, FCO 8/954.
                                                      89
                                                           Caradon (New York) to Foreign Office, 30 December 1969, FCO 8/954.
                                                      90
                                                           Warner (New York) to Foreign Office, 29 January 1970, FCO 8/1364.
                                                      91
                                                           Wright (Zurich) to Foreign Office, 6 February 1970, FCO 8/1365.


                                                                                                                                                   173
                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                      1970, Vakil delivered the formal Iranian approach to U Thant, asking him to use
                                                      his Good Offices ‘with a view to ascertaining the true wishes of the people of
                                                      Bahrain with respect to the future status of the Islands of Bahrain by appointing a
                                                      Personal Representative to carry out this Mission’. After a short interval designed
                                                      to avoid any appearance of collusion, the British informed U Thant that the Iranian
                                                      proposal was ‘acceptable’.92
                                                         With the negotiations completed, it remained for the United Nations to carry out
                                                      its Mission in Bahrain and for Iran to recognize Bahrain’s independence. In
                                                      August 1969 the Iranians had proposed Vittorio Winspeare Guicciardi, an Italian
                                                      diplomat who was then Director-General of the UN Office at Geneva, as a possible
                                                      PRSG for the UN Mission to Bahrain.93 After speaking with Winspeare in
                                                      November 1969, the British concluded that ‘we can be reasonably confident that
                                                      he will act in accordance with whatever is agreed’ between Britain, Bahrain and
                                                      the UN.94 Winspeare was chosen by U Thant to be his PRSG, and together with
                                                      Ralph Bunche and Sir Geoffrey Arthur of the British Foreign Office, he met with
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      the Bahrainis in Geneva in December 1969 and assured them that he would abide
                                                      by whatever method they had agreed to with the British for ascertaining the wishes
                                                      of the Bahraini people.95 With the British, Bahrainis and the United Nations all in
                                                      agreement, and with the Bahrainis having prepared their population for the UN
                                                      Mission’s arrival, the findings of the UN Mission were a foregone conclusion.
                                                         While the Bahrainis were preparing their public for the UN Mission’s arrival,
                                                      the Shah also took steps to prepare Iranian public opinion for the abandonment of
                                                      Iran’s claim to Bahrain. Pamphlets were distributed within the armed forces, the
                                                      civil service and the universities explaining why the claim was unsustainable.96
                                                      The only opposition from within the Shah’s inner circle came from Zahedi, who
                                                      consulted widely with Iran’s political and military elite to see whether any military
                                                      option was feasible for holding on to Bahrain.97 He took the bold step of taking a
                                                      number of senior officials from the Foreign Ministry to discuss Iran’s claim to
                                                      Bahrain with the Shah on 14 January 1970, perhaps in a last-ditch effort to change
                                                      his Sovereign’s mind. During this audience the Shah explained to his diplomats
                                                      that Bahrain was of little value to Iran and giving up the claim would help foster
                                                      the necessary conditions for Iran to assume a leadership role in the Gulf.
                                                      Moreover, he explained that he had no intention of becoming a ‘Don Quixote’ by
                                                      using the military to enforce Iranian sovereignty over Bahrain.98 Indeed, even
                                                      Zahedi finally concluded that any use of force would only result in Iran’s regional
                                                      isolation.99
                                                         U Thant was set to announce the UN Mission on 28 March 1970, and the Iranian
                                                      Government planned to convene an emergency session of the Majlis the next day
                                                       92
                                                          Crawford (Bahrain) to Foreign Office, 21 May 1970, FCO 8/1372; and ‘Note by the Secretary-General’,
                                                      United Nations Security Council, 28 March 1970, S/9726.
                                                       93
                                                          Wright (Tehran) to Foreign Office, 11 August 1969, FCO 8/948.
                                                       94
                                                          Caradon (New York) to Foreign Office, 26 November 1969, FCO 8/952.
                                                       95
                                                          Melville (Geneva) to Foreign Office, 31 December 1969, FCO 8/1363; and Al-Baharna ‘The Fact-finding
                                                      Mission’, p. 545.
                                                       96
                                                          Wright (Tehran) to Foreign Office, 6 July 1970, FCO 8/1372; and Moghtader, ‘The Settlement of the Bahrain
                                                      Question’, p. 24, f. 1.
                                                       97
                                                          Interview with Ardeshir Zahedi, 27 September 2007, Montreux.
                                                       98
                                                          Faridun Zandfard, Khatirat-i khidmat dar Vizarat-i Umur-i Kharijah: simha-yi diplumatik-i nuvin-i Iran
                                                      (Tehran: Nashr-i Abi, 2004), pp. 94–95; and Fereydun Hoveyda in an interview with Mahnaz Afkhami, 20 June
                                                      1988, New York, in the Oral History of Iran Collection of the Foundation for Iranian Studies, Tape 1B.
                                                       99
                                                          Interview with Ardeshir Zahedi, 27 September 2007, Montreux.


                                                      174
                                                                                                                        THE BAHRAIN QUESTION, 1968–1970

                                                      to inform the nation that if the Winspeare Mission found that the people of Bahrain
                                                      sought independence, and the UN Security Council endorsed these findings, then
                                                      Iran would renounce her claim. To pre-empt any opposition in the Majlis, Premier
                                                      Hoveyda held a meeting on 26 March 1970 with the leaders of the parliamentary
                                                      factions at the home of Mohsen Pezechgpour, leader of the small far-right Pan-
                                                      Iranist Party. Although the Pan-Iranists controlled only a handful of seats in the
                                                      Majlis, they were staunch advocates of the Iranian claim to Bahrain. Abbas Ali
                                                      Khalatbari, who had replaced Afshar as Permanent Secretary of the Foreign
                                                      Ministry, accompanied Hoveyda. Khalatbari explained to the assembled
                                                      parliamentary leaders that Bahrain was of little economic or strategic value to
                                                      Iran and that enforcing Iran’s claim would mean an unpalatable and costly military
                                                      intervention. Hoveyda turned to Pezechgpour and informed him that if the Pan-
                                                      Iranists cooperated they would be rewarded with more than 30 seats in the next
                                                      Majlis. If they did not, there would be severe consequences.100
                                                         According to Alam, neither Hoveyda nor Zahedi wanted to accept the odious
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      task of informing the Majlis that Iran intended to abandon her claim to Bahrain.101
                                                      In an act of cruel irony the Shah finally ordered Zahedi, the staunchest defender of
                                                      Iran’s claim, to deliver the news to the Majlis on 29 March 1970. Despite
                                                      Hoveyda’s efforts, Pezechgpour denounced the Shah’s decision from the Majlis
                                                      floor.102 The Shah was reportedly furious with Pezechgpour and the Pan-Iranists.
                                                      Their offices in Khuzistan province were closed and their party newspaper was
                                                      shut down, its publishers jailed.103 However, besides the Pan-Iranists’ protests in
                                                      the Majlis, there is no evidence of any public outcry against the Shah’s decision.
                                                      The heavily censored print media presented the decision as an Iranian victory over
                                                      British imperialism.104
                                                         After this minor disturbance, the rest of the scripted exercise unfolded without
                                                      incident. Winspeare arrived in Bahrain on 30 March 1970 and finished his
                                                      consultations by 13 April.105 His report found that ‘the overwhelming majority of
                                                      the people of Bahrain wish to gain recognition of their identity in a fully
                                                      independent and sovereign State free to decide for itself its relations with other
                                                      States’.106 According to Wright, the report was greeted by the Iranians with ‘smug
                                                      self-congratulation’.107 Both Iran and Britain immediately requested that the UN
                                                      Security Council convene to consider Winspeare’s findings. It was imperative for
                                                      the Shah that Winspeare’s report should receive the Security Council’s stamp of
                                                      international approval. The Council convened on 11 May 1970 and unanimously
                                                      adopted Resolution 278, which endorsed Winspeare’s report and welcomed its
                                                      findings.108
                                                      100
                                                          See Mohsen Pezechgpour in an interview recorded by Zia Sadeghi, 31 March 1984, Paris, tape nos. 8 and 9,
                                                      Iranian Oral History Collection, Harvard University.
                                                      101
                                                          Alam, The Shah and I, p. 135.
                                                      102
                                                          Iran National Consultative Assembly, Muzakirat-i Majlis-i Shura-yi Milli, 22nd Majlis, 182nd to 202nd
                                                      Sessions, 9 Farvardin to 16 Tir 1349 (Tehran: Majlis Printing Office), pp. 1–9.
                                                      103
                                                          Alam, The Shah and I, p. 140. See Mohsen Pezechgpour in an interview recorded by Zia Sadeghi, 31 March
                                                      1984, Paris, tape no. 9, Iranian Oral History Collection, Harvard University.
                                                      104
                                                          Wright (Tehran) to Foreign Office, 6 July 1970, FCO 8/1372.
                                                      105
                                                          Crawford (Bahrain) to Foreign Office, 21 May 1970, FCO 8/1372; Winspeare (Bahrain) to U Thant
                                                      (New York), 17 April 1970, S-0279-0016-10, United Nations Archives and Records Management Section, New
                                                      York; and Jensen, ‘The Secretary-General’s Use of Good Offices’, pp. 341–342.
                                                      106
                                                          ‘Note by the Secretary-General’, United Nations Security Council, 30 April 1970, S/9772, p. 13.
                                                      107
                                                          Wright (Tehran) to Foreign Office, 6 July 1970, FCO 8/1372.
                                                      108
                                                          United Nations. Security Council, Resolution 278, 11 May 1970, S/RES/278.


                                                                                                                                                             175
                                                      ROHAM ALVANDI

                                                         The wishes of the Bahraini people had now been ascertained and recognized
                                                      by the United Nations. All that was left was for Iran’s legislature to ratify the
                                                      decision. The Majlis was promptly convened on 14 May and passed a motion
                                                      identical to Resolution 278 by a vote of 187 to 4, with only the Pan-Iranists voting
                                                      against the motion.109 Four days later the Iranian Senate convened, where all 60
                                                      senators voted in favour of the same motion.110 The Iranian claim to Bahrain had
                                                      been abandoned with little public or private protest. Aside from the objections
                                                      voiced by Pan-Iranists, there were murmurings of discontent among staff officers
                                                      in the Imperial Iranian Navy. For example, Admiral Kamal Habibollahi privately
                                                      expressed doubts about the validity of the UN Mission’s findings and was of the
                                                      opinion that giving away Bahrain was a major strategic mistake because it meant
                                                      surrendering control of the southern portion of the Gulf. The Shah was certainly
                                                      aware of this disquiet and he went in person to the Iranian Admiralty to explain to
                                                      his naval commanders why maintaining the claim to Bahrain was no longer in
                                                      Iran’s interests.111
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                         The abandonment of Iran’s claim to Bahrain contributed to a dramatic
                                                      improvement in Egyptian– Iranian relations. The decline of Nasser’s power
                                                      following Israel’s decisive victory over Egypt in the June 1967 War, along with
                                                      Iran and Egypt’s shared animosity towards the Ba’thist regime that had come to
                                                      power in Iraq in July 1968, had led to an easing of tensions between the Shah and
                                                      Nasser. Through the mediation efforts of various Arab leaders, Iran and Egypt
                                                      began discussions in May 1970 for a resumption of diplomatic relations, which
                                                      had been severed by Nasser a decade earlier. The Shah’s decision to abandon
                                                      Bahrain was undoubtedly responsible for the timing of the resumption of
                                                      diplomatic relations between Tehran and Cairo on 29 August 1970. Furthermore,
                                                      Iran’s relations with the Gulf sheikhdoms also improved, leading to continental
                                                      shelf agreements with Kuwait in July 1970 and with Bahrain in June 1971.112
                                                         This Arab– Iranian rapprochement strengthened Iran’s position when the time
                                                      came to settle the Islands dispute. Following months of negotiations with the
                                                      British and the Rulers of Sharjah and Ras Al-Khaimah, the Shah deployed his
                                                      troops on the Islands on 30 November 1971, one day before Britain’s treaty
                                                      obligations to the Rulers expired. Iran had reached an agreement with the Ruler of
                                                      Sharjah on Abu Musa, and according to Admiral Ramzi Abbas-Attaie, who
                                                      oversaw the deployment of Iranian troops on Abu Musa, a representative of the
                                                      Ruler of Sharjah accompanied the Iranian forces when they landed.113 No such
                                                      agreement was reached with Ras Al-Khaimah on the Tunbs, and when the Iranian
                                                      troops landed on those islands they were met with minor resistance resulting in
                                                      109
                                                          Wright (Tehran) to Foreign Office, 6 July 1970, FCO 8/1372.
                                                      110
                                                          Wright (Tehran) to Foreign Office, 6 July 1970, FCO 8/1372; and Ramazani, ‘The Settlement of the Bahrain
                                                      Dispute’, p. 53.
                                                      111
                                                          See Adm. Kamal Habibollahi in an interview recorded by Zia Sadeghi, 15 December 1984, Fairfax,
                                                      Virginia, tape no. 2, Iranian Oral History Collection, Harvard University.
                                                      112
                                                          Rouhollah Ramazani, ‘Arab–Iranian Relations in Modern Time’, in Ehsan Yarshater (ed.), Encyclopaedia
                                                      Iranica, Vol. II (London: Routledge, 1987), pp. 221–222; and Chubin and Zabih, The Foreign Relations of
                                                      Iran, pp. 163–169.
                                                      113
                                                          See Adm. Ramzi Abbas-Attaie in an interview recorded by Shahla Haeri, 11 June 1985, Sherman Oaks, CA,
                                                      tape no. 1, Iranian Oral History Collection, Harvard University. For the full text of this agreement, see ‘Appendix
                                                      1: Anglo-Iranian Memorandum of Understanding 1971’, in Hooshang Amirahmadi (ed.), Small Islands, Big
                                                      Politics: The Tonbs and Abu Musa in the Gulf (London: Macmillan, 1996), pp. 161 –175.




                                                      176
                                                                                                                        THE BAHRAIN QUESTION, 1968–1970

                                                      some casualties.114 Thanks to the Shah’s acquiescence on Bahrain, the Arab
                                                      World’s reaction to Iran’s military deployment on the Islands was greatly muted.
                                                      Only Iraq severed diplomatic relations with Iran, and through the Arab League,
                                                      tried to persuade the other Arab states to do likewise. Iraq, along with Libya,
                                                      Algeria and South Yemen, lodged a protest with the UN Security Council.
                                                      However, when the Council met on 10 December 1971 to consider the dispute, it
                                                      took no action against Iran and instead opted to postpone the matter. Egypt limited
                                                      itself to calling on Iran to withdraw and reach a ‘peaceful and just solution’.115
                                                         Soon after concluding the Bahrain negotiations on 5 February 1970 in St
                                                      Moritz, the Shah was joined on his annual skiing vacation by his close friend and
                                                      advisor Asadollah Alam. On the way to the ski slopes the two childhood friends
                                                      chatted about the negotiations that had just been concluded. The Shah candidly
                                                      asked Alam: ‘Between ourselves, do you suppose that we are acting as traitors to
                                                      our country by going ahead with this settlement over Bahrain?’.116 Despite more
                                                      than two years of torturous negotiations to find a face-saving formula for him to
Downloaded by [86.149.152.143] at 07:06 01 May 2012




                                                      abandon Iran’s claim, the Shah still feared the judgement of Iranian public
                                                      opinion. He had long ago concluded that Bahrain was of little strategic value to
                                                      Iran. In 1968 when the British announced that they would leave the Gulf in three
                                                      years time, the Iranian claim became an obstacle to the Shah’s efforts to foster
                                                      Arab– Iranian cooperation on regional security. His decision to abandon Bahrain
                                                      was driven by a strategic calculation that Arab– Iranian cooperation would both
                                                      prevent the penetration of the Gulf by radical Arab forces and also create the
                                                      necessary conditions for Iran to assume a leadership role in the region.
                                                      Nonetheless, what the record of these secret Anglo-Iranian negotiations suggests is
                                                      that the Shah’s abiding fear of the judgement of Iranian public opinion constrained
                                                      his ability to conduct foreign policy.

                                                      Acknowledgements
                                                      The author is grateful to Louise Fawcett, Avi Shlaim, and Wilfred Knapp for their
                                                      helpful comments on an earlier draft, and to the British Institute of Persian Studies
                                                      for their generous support for this research.




